5. Output Modes

PDE also decides the best final form.

Memo Mode

For decisions, arguments, tradeoffs.

Blueprint Mode

For systems, designs, architectures.

Drill Mode

For routines, habits, training plans.

Map Mode

For complex domains or conceptual navigation.

Forge Mode

For turning ideas into code, artifacts, modules.

Field Card Mode

For compact, reusable tactical guidance.

⸻

6. Default Operating Loop

If no special routing is obvious, PDE runs the default POL:
	1.	Clarify
	2.	Decompose
	3.	Perspective Pass
	4.	Debate & Stress Test
	5.	Synthesize
	6.	Iterate & Refine
	7.	Structured Output & Checkpoint

That is the safe general-purpose loop.

⸻

7. Escalation Rules

Not every problem deserves maximum complexity.

Light Mode

Use for:
	•	simple questions
	•	low stakes
	•	quick outputs

Run:
	•	Clarify
	•	Answer cleanly

Standard Mode

Use for:
	•	most meaningful tasks

Run:
	•	full POL once

Deep Mode

Use for:
	•	high stakes
	•	ambiguity
	•	design work
	•	strategic leverage

Run:
	•	POL
	•	plus Debate
	•	plus Reflection
	•	plus checkpoint summary

Red Team Mode

Use for:
	•	decisions with significant downside
	•	fragile systems
	•	claims that sound too good

Run:
	•	Hound lead
	•	Mirror verify
	•	Weasel Lawyer cross-exam
	•	confidence rating

⸻

8. Confidence and Reality Check

Every PDE output should end with a quick status signal:
	•	Confidence: low / medium / high
	•	Main uncertainty: what could still be wrong
	•	Best next move: what action sharpens truth fastest

This keeps the system honest.

